Certainly! Here are a few more examples demonstrating how to use a checkbox to switch CSS variables using only CSS.

### Example 1: Font size toggle

We'll toggle between two different font sizes for a paragraph:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <style>
        :root {
            --font-size: 16px;
        }

        .text {
            font-size: var(--font-size);
            transition: font-size 0.3s;
        }

        #size-toggle:checked ~ .text {
            --font-size: 24px;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <label for="size-toggle">Toggle Font Size</label>
    <input type="checkbox" id="size-toggle">
    <p class="text">This is a paragraph with toggleable font size.</p>
</body>
</html>
```

### Example 2: Theme switcher

Toggle between a light theme and a dark theme using a checkbox:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <style>
        :root {
            --background: #fff;
            --text-color: #000;
        }

        body {
            background-color: var(--background);
            color: var(--text-color);
            transition: background-color 0.3s, color 0.3s;
        }

        #theme-toggle:checked ~ body {
            --background: #333;
            --text-color: #fff;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <label for="theme-toggle">Toggle Dark/Light Theme</label>
    <input type="checkbox" id="theme-toggle">
    <div>
        <p>This is a text element that changes color based on the theme.</p>
    </div>
</body>
</html>
```

### Example 3: CSS Grid layout switch

Switch between two different CSS Grid layouts (e.g., column count) with a checkbox:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <style>
        :root {
            --grid-columns: 2;
        }

        .grid-container {
            display: grid;
            grid-template-columns: repeat(var(--grid-columns), 1fr);
            gap: 10px;
            transition: grid-template-columns 0.3s;
        }

        #layout-toggle:checked ~ .grid-container {
            --grid-columns: 4;
        }

        .grid-item {
            background-color: #e0e0e0;
            padding: 20px;
            text-align: center;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <label for="layout-toggle">Toggle Grid Layout</label>
    <input type="checkbox" id="layout-toggle">
    <div class="grid-container">
        <div class="grid-item">Item 1</div>
        <div class="grid-item">Item 2</div>
        <div class="grid-item">Item 3</div>
        <div class="grid-item">Item 4</div>
    </div>
</body>
</html>
```

These examples showcase the power and versatility of CSS variables and pseudo-classes, providing a method for creating dynamic interfaces without JavaScript. The `:checked` pseudo-class combined with sibling combinators allows the styling to be contingent on the state of a checkbox input, thus enabling a variety of user-controlled style changes.

