Yes, the sibling combinator in CSS works regardless of the depth or number of siblings between the two elements, as long as they share the same parent and the first element precedes the second one in the document tree. The key point is that the sibling selectors (either the adjacent sibling combinator `+` or the general sibling combinator `~`) do not traverse up or down the DOM tree; they only look at sibling elements at the same level of the hierarchy following the source element.

The adjacent sibling combinator `+` will target the immediate sibling following the source element:

```css
/* targets any .target immediately after .source */
.source + .target {
    /* styles */
}
```

The general sibling combinator `~` will target all siblings following the source element at the same hierarchy level:

```css
/* targets all .target elements following .source */
.source ~ .target {
    /* styles */
}
```

Here is an example showing that the depth does not matter for the general sibling combinator `~`:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <style>
        :root {
            --background-color: #ffffff; /* Default background color */
        }

        .content {
            padding: 20px;
            background-color: var(--background-color);
            transition: background-color 0.3s;
        }

        #theme-toggler:checked ~ .wrapper .content {
            --background-color: #000000; /* New background color when checkbox is checked */
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>

    <label for="theme-toggler">Toggle Dark/Light Theme</label>
    <input type="checkbox" id="theme-toggler">

    <div class="wrapper">
        <!-- Arbitrary depth of siblings -->
        <div class="inner-wrapper">
            <div class="another-wrapper">
                <div class="content">
                    This is a content area that changes background color.
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>

</body>
</html>
```

In this example, the `#theme-toggler:checked ~ .wrapper .content` selector targets the `.content` class styled within the `.wrapper`, regardless of how deeply nested it is, as long as it is at any depth of siblings following the `#theme-toggler`. The `~` combinator targets the `.wrapper`, and from there we descend down the tree to reach `.content`.

Please note that all preceding siblings must follow the same parent for the sibling combinator to apply the styles. If your checkbox is nested within other elements or in a different parent, you may need to adjust your HTML structure or use JavaScript to achieve the desired effect.

In CSS, there is no explicit "unchecked" pseudo-class modifier. However, you can achieve the effect of styling an unchecked element by using the absence of the `:checked` pseudo-class. The styles you define for the element outside of the `:checked` state will be applied when the checkbox is not checked.

Here is an example of how you might define the default styles for an element when the checkbox is unchecked, and override those styles when the checkbox is checked:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <style>
        input[type="checkbox"] {
            /* Styles that apply to the checkbox regardless of its checked state */
        }

        .content {
            /* Default styles applied when the checkbox is not checked */
            background: lightgray;
            color: black;
            padding: 10px;
        }

        input[type="checkbox"]:checked + .content {
            /* Styles applied only when the checkbox is checked */
            background: darkgray;
            color: white;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>

    <label for="toggle-checkbox">Toggle Styles</label>
    <input type="checkbox" id="toggle-checkbox">
    <div class="content">
        This content will change styles when the checkbox is checked.
    </div>

</body>
</html>
```

In this example, `.content` will have a light background and black text by default (when the checkbox is not checked), and will switch to a dark background with white text when the checkbox is checked. The absence of the `:checked` pseudo-class effectively acts as the "unchecked" state for the checkbox.

It's important to note that the default styles will be applied to the element unless overridden by more specific selectors or by a change in state (such as ticking the checkbox, which activates the `:checked` selector). Thus, there's no need for an "unchecked" pseudo-class; you simply style the element for its default (unchecked) state and define additional styles for when it is in its checked state.

In PHP, you can create a simple hash function that produces an output with a maximum length of 8 characters by using built-in functions. Since you want the output to be 8 characters, we can use a combination of `crc32` which gives you a 32-bit hash, and then convert it to base 36 (or base 16 if you prefer hex format) to condense it. However, be aware that shortening the hash length increases the probability of collisions.

Here's an example hash function using `crc32` with base 36 conversion:

```php
function shortHash($input) {
    // Calculate the CRC32 hash of the input
    $hash = crc32($input);

    // Convert the hash to a Base 36 (0-9, a-z) string and ensure it's 8 characters
    $shortHash = str_pad(base_convert($hash, 10, 36), 8, '0', STR_PAD_LEFT);

    return $shortHash;
}

$inputData = "YourDataHere";
$hash = shortHash($inputData);
echo $hash;
```

Another option would be to use a portion of the `md5` hash, which produces a 32-character hexadecimal number. We can take the first 8 characters to get a short hash:

```php
function shortHashMd5($input) {
    // Calculate the MD5 hash of the input
    $hash = md5($input);

    // Return the first 8 characters of the hash
    $shortHash = substr($hash, 0, 8);

    return $shortHash;
}

$inputData = "YourDataHere";
$hash = shortHashMd5($inputData);
echo $hash;
```

Remember that by limiting the hash length to 8 characters, you're significantly reducing the space and uniqueness of the hash. This is not secure for cryptographic purposes and should not be used where collisions might cause security issues. These functions are mainly for creating identifiers or checksum-like values.
